  "prompt": "What is the transpose of a matrix ?",
  "response": "The transpose of a matrix is an operation that flips the matrix over its diagonal, switching the row and column indices of each element. If you have a matrix \\( A \\) with dimensions \\( m \\times n \\), its transpose, denoted by \\( A^T \\) or \\( A' \\), will have dimensions \\( n \\times m \\).\n\nFor example, if you have a matrix:\n\n\\[\nA = \\begin{bmatrix}\na & b & c \\\\\nd & e & f\n\\end{bmatrix}\n\\]\n\nThe transpose of \\( A \\) is:\n\n\\[\nA^T = \\begin{bmatrix}\na & d \\\\\nb & e \\\\\nc & f\n\\end{bmatrix}\n\\]\n\nEach element \\( a_{ij} \\) of the original matrix \\( A \\) becomes the element \\( a_{ji} \\) in the transposed matrix \\( A^T \\). Transposing is useful in various mathematical and computational contexts, such as solving systems of linear equations, matrix calculus, and more.",
